00405                 /**************************************************************************************************************
00406                  *                                      Macros
00407                  *
00408                  * Sorry about all the messy macros, but they do make the RISC operations _much_ simpler and a whole lot less
00409                  * cut-n-pasted code.  All these macros ultimately make calls to the sub-policy RISC operations.
00410                  *
00411                  * The macros come in two broad categories:  those with "_SUBS_" in their name call the sub-policy operations for
00412                  * all sub-policies that are enabled and whose input argument values are valid.  Those with "_SUB_" in their
00413                  * name call only one sub-policy (indicated by the first argument) and only when that sub-policy is enabled and
00414                  * its input arguments are valid.
00415                  *
00416                  * Within each of those two broad categories, there are three subcategories:  All names have a digit that
00417                  * indicates the number of input (not total) arguments to the RISC operation.  If the number is followed by an
00418                  * "x" then the last macro argument is the argument list for the RISC operation.  If the macro name ends with
00419                  * "NR" then the RISC operation does not return a value.
00420                  *
00421                  * The OPAND_x arguments must be multi-policy values.  A sub-policy is called only if all the inputs are marked
00422                  * as valid and the sub-policy is enabled.
00423                  *
00424                  * For the "x" versions of these macros, the last macro argument, ARGLIST, should be the argument list passed
00425                  * to the sub-policy.  If any of those arguments are multi-policy values then they should be appended with
00426                  * ".get_subvalue(tag)", which selects the appropriate sub-value depending on the sub-policy being called (see
00427                  * the writeRegister() operation for an example).
00428                  *
00429                  * Finally, if a macro has a "b" in the last component (like CALL_SUBS_1b) then it handles a RISC operation
00430                  * that takes two template arguments.  It's done this way because an operation like "extract<from,to>" gets
00431                  * parsed as two macro arguments that have to be reassembled in the macro body.
00432                  **************************************************************************************************************/
00433 
00434 /* Macros to invoke a RISC operation in a single sub-policy.  The arguments to pass to the sub-policy's operation are listed
00435  * explicitly. */
00436 #define CALL_SUB_0x(TAG, OPERATION, RETVAL,                            ARGLIST)                                                \
00437                 do {                                                                                                           \
00438                     if (should_call(TAG))                                                                                      \
00439                         (RETVAL).set_subvalue(TAG, get_policy(TAG).OPERATION ARGLIST);                                         \
00440                 } while (0)
00441 #define CALL_SUB_1x(TAG, OPERATION, RETVAL, OPAND_A,                   ARGLIST)                                                \
00442                 do {                                                                                                           \
00443                     if (should_call(TAG, (OPAND_A)))                                                                           \
00444                         (RETVAL).set_subvalue(TAG, get_policy(TAG).OPERATION ARGLIST);                                         \
00445                 } while (0)
00446 #define CALL_SUB_1bx(TAG, OPERATION, TPL0, RETVAL, OPAND_A,            ARGLIST)                                                \
00447                 do {                                                                                                           \
00448                     if (should_call(TAG, (OPAND_A)))                                                                           \
00449                         (RETVAL).set_subvalue(TAG, get_policy(TAG).OPERATION, TPL0 ARGLIST);                                   \
00450                 } while (0)
00451 #define CALL_SUB_2x(TAG, OPERATION, RETVAL, OPAND_A, OPAND_B,          ARGLIST)                                                \
00452                 do {                                                                                                           \
00453                     if (should_call(TAG, (OPAND_A), (OPAND_B)))                                                                \
00454                         (RETVAL).set_subvalue(TAG, get_policy(TAG).OPERATION ARGLIST);                                         \
00455                 } while (0)
00456 #define CALL_SUB_3x(TAG, OPERATION, RETVAL, OPAND_A, OPAND_B, OPAND_C, ARGLIST)                                                \
00457                 do {                                                                                                           \
00458                     if (should_call(TAG, (OPAND_A), (OPAND_B), (OPAND_C)))                                                     \
